# AKOS External-Render Discipline — Six-Surface Delivery Contract

Use this rule whenever authoring, editing, or proposing to **deliver** prose to any non-cleared audience: investors (J-IN), customers (J-CU), partners (J-PT), advisors (J-AD pre-NDA), regulators (J-ENISA), recruiters (J-RC), or external collaborators (J-CO). Codifies decision **D-IH-86-P** (operator ratified at 2026-05-19, post-Bundle D closure: *"i can't send .md. no one will see them except our collaborators. for externals, pdf only or a web or erp or mail or something like that. let it be canon"*).

This rule is the **delivery-format axis**. Its sister rule [`akos-brand-baseline-reality.mdc`](akos-brand-baseline-reality.mdc) governs the **vocabulary-register axis** (CORPINT-internal vs translated-external). The two are orthogonal and stack: any external delivery must satisfy *both* — translated register AND rendered surface. Markdown that is jargon-clean but un-rendered still violates the discipline because no external recipient should be reading raw markdown.

The paired skill [`.cursor/skills/external-render-craft/SKILL.md`](../skills/external-render-craft/SKILL.md) carries the *how* layer (which script renders which surface, what the soft-success fallback is, where the artifact lands, what the sha256 trail looks like). This rule is the *when*.

## The doctrine in one sentence

**External recipients receive rendered surfaces — PDF, Web, ERP, Mail, Slide, or Broadcast — never raw markdown files; markdown is the SSOT for content authoring; rendering is the act of crossing the trust boundary into a non-cleared audience.**

## RULE 1 — Six-surface canonical enum (binding)

Every artifact intended for an external recipient must be delivered through exactly one (or composed across multiple) of the following six surfaces:

| Code | Surface | Defining property | Examples in this repo |
|:---|:---|:---|:---|
| **`pdf`** | Portable Document Format | Self-contained file the recipient can open offline; sealed with sha256 in a manifest sidecar | `artifacts/exports/dossier-enisa-PRJ-HOL-FOUNDING-2026-2026-04-29.pdf` (via `scripts/render_dossier.py`); `artifacts/exports/holistika-company-dossier-enisa-2026-04-30.pdf` (via `scripts/export_company_deck_pdf.py`) |
| **`web`** | Deployed page on a registered domain | Publicly addressable URL; the recipient hits an HTTP(S) endpoint and reads HTML | `holistikaresearch.com/...` (boilerplate-rendered); `kirbe.com/...`; `hlk-erp.app/(public)/...` public route |
| **`erp`** | Sealed record inside the ERP / CRM | The recipient logs into a system (HLK-ERP panel; KiRBe portal; Stripe-portal sealed record) and reads the artifact gated behind their authenticated identity | `kirbe-platform/...` engagement panel routes; `hlk-erp/app/[panels]/...` |
| **`mail`** | Rendered HTML body inside an email | The body of the email itself, NOT a link to a markdown file; produced from `cover_email_*.md` SSOT via mail-rendering pipeline | `cover_email_es.md` rendered into mail body at SMTP-send time |
| **`slide`** | Deck export (Figma frame export OR HTML-to-PDF deck render) | A presentation-shaped artifact (1:1 sender to one or many viewers) | The 14-slide founding deck: Figma file `yiPav7BLxUulNFrrsoKJqW` + HTML preview at `docs/presentations/holistika-company-dossier/index.html` + PDF export via `scripts/export_company_deck_pdf.py` |
| **`broadcast`** | Published 1:N surface meant for many recipients at once | Distinct from `web` because it is *intentionally* multicast (blog post, press kit, shared deck link, registered case study); distinct from `mail` because the recipient list is open-ended | `docs/presentations/<engagement>/index.html` published to a stable URL; press-kit pages on `holistikaresearch.com/press/`; shared deck links on Figma; case-study pages |

**Extension rule:** when a new surface emerges that doesn't fit any of the six (e.g., voice-rendered audio briefings; SMS bundles; interactive notebooks), an initiative must amend this enum + add a row to the matrix in §RULE 2 + extend [`scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py`](../../scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py) before the new surface ships externally. No silent additions.

## RULE 2 — Audience-class → render-format matrix (binding; mechanically enforced)

Audience tags from [`AUDIENCE_REGISTRY.csv`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/People/Compliance/canonicals/dimensions/AUDIENCE_REGISTRY.csv) (I85 P2) determine which render surfaces are acceptable per audience:

| Audience tag | Acceptable surfaces | Notes |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **`J-IN` (Investor)** | `pdf` ; `slide` ; `broadcast` ; `web` | Investors typically want a sealed deck (PDF or slide-shared link) + a public hero page (web). Mail body is acceptable for cover; the dossier itself must be PDF. **Never .md.** |
| **`J-CU` (Customer SME)** | `pdf` ; `web` ; `mail` ; `erp` | Customers want a proposal PDF or a web product page or a sealed ERP-gated quote. Mail body for outreach. **Never .md.** |
| **`J-PT` (Partner)** | `pdf` ; `web` ; `mail` ; `erp` ; `broadcast` | Partners want a partnership brief (PDF), a partner-program page (web/broadcast), or a portal record (erp). **Never .md.** |
| **`J-AD` (Advisor)** | `pdf` ; `mail` ; `erp` (post-NDA: also `web` if the advisor's dashboard is gated) | Pre-NDA: PDF + mail only. Post-NDA: ERP-gated handoff packs become acceptable per [`akos-adviser-engagement.mdc`](akos-adviser-engagement.mdc). **Never .md** even post-NDA. |
| **`J-ENISA` (Regulator)** | `pdf` (mandatory; sealed sha256 trail) | ENISA reviewers consume **PDF only** with the sha256 manifest as the integrity claim. Mail body is acceptable for cover correspondence; the dossier MUST be PDF with sealed trail. **Never .md, never web.** |
| **`J-RC` (Recruiter)** | `pdf` ; `web` ; `mail` ; `broadcast` | Recruiters want job posts (web/broadcast) + role briefs (PDF) + outreach (mail). **Never .md.** Currently `inactive` per registry; flips to active per I75. |
| **`J-CO` (Collaborator)** | `pdf` ; `web` ; `broadcast` ; `mail` | Methodology peers + open-source contributors. Currently `planned`. **Never .md** when surface is intentionally external; .md is fine when surface is a public README that the collaborator reads via GitHub web UI (which is `web` surface, not `.md` delivery). |
| **`J-OP` (Operator internal)** | `.md` (markdown-OK) | Operator + cleared agents + AICs consuming internal CORPINT register. **This is the only audience for which raw markdown is the canonical delivery.** Validators MUST exempt J-OP-only-tagged surfaces from render-trail enforcement. |

The matrix is enforced mechanically by [`scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py`](../../scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py) (created at this rule's mint commit). The validator FK-resolves `audience:` frontmatter against `AUDIENCE_REGISTRY.csv`, then for any surface tagged with at least one external audience class, checks for a paired render artifact via the heuristics in §RULE 4.

## RULE 3 — Markdown-as-SSOT, render-as-delivery (binding)

This rule does **not** prohibit authoring in markdown. Markdown is the canonical authoring substrate for almost every prose surface in this repo, including external-delivery surfaces. The discipline is:

1. **`.md` is the SSOT for content** — the words, structure, and semantic meaning live in `.md` (or `.yaml` for slide content).
2. **Rendering is the trust-boundary crossing** — the act of producing a PDF / web / ERP / mail / slide / broadcast artifact is the act of preparing content for an external recipient.
3. **External delivery references the rendered artifact**, not the `.md` source — cover emails attach the PDF, not the markdown. Web pages are linked by URL, not by source path. ERP records carry the rendered HTML/PDF, not the markdown.
4. **Rendered artifacts carry sha256 manifests** — every PDF/HTML render writes a `.manifest.json` sidecar at the same path with `source_sha256` + `render_sha256` + `rendered_at` + `render_tool` + `render_version` (per [Initiative 24 G-24-3](../../docs/wip/planning/24-hlk-evidence-integrity/master-roadmap.md) closure trail). The manifest is the integrity claim that backstops the rendered artifact.

## RULE 4 — Render-trail detection heuristics (for the drift gate)

[`scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py`](../../scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py) detects whether a tagged-external surface has a paired render artifact via these heuristics, in order:

1. **PDF heuristic.** For a markdown at `<engagement>/<dossier_or_handoff>.md`, look for a paired PDF at `artifacts/exports/<derived-stem>.pdf` OR a `paths.pdf` slot in a sibling `*.manifest.md`. Resolve via `scripts/render_dossier.py --dry-run` if the output path is parameterised.
2. **Web heuristic.** Look for a sibling `web-link.md` or a `paths.web` slot in a sibling `*.manifest.md` containing a stable URL (must match `https?://` regex; must not be a `file://` or `localhost` URL). Empty / placeholder URLs do not satisfy the heuristic.
3. **ERP heuristic.** Look for a sibling `erp-record.md` containing a `record_id:` field with a non-empty UUID-shaped value, OR a `paths.erp_record_id` slot in the manifest.
4. **Mail heuristic.** For a `cover_email_*.md`, look for a paired `cover_email_*.html` rendered body OR a `mail-render.md` sibling that records the SMTP-send-time render policy (e.g., "rendered inline at send via `scripts/render_cover_email.py` — body sha256 captured per send").
5. **Slide heuristic.** For deck-shaped content (`deck_*.md` or `deck_*.yaml`), look for a sibling `figma-link.md` with a non-empty Figma URL OR a paired PDF in `artifacts/exports/` matching the deck-export naming pattern.
6. **Broadcast heuristic.** Look for a sibling `broadcast-link.md` or a `paths.broadcast` slot containing a stable URL on `holistikaresearch.com`, `kirbe.com`, or another registered domain (must match the registered-domain allow-list).

**Exemption rules:**

- **J-OP-only surfaces** (markdown carries `audience: J-OP` exclusively) are exempt entirely.
- **Manifest-shaped surfaces** (`*.manifest.md`, `topic_*.md` Output-1 manifests per Initiative 25) are exempt — they are governance scaffolding, not external prose. Detection: filename matches `*.manifest.md` OR `topic_*.md` OR file is under `docs/references/hlk/v3.0/_assets/<plane>/<program>/<topic>/topic_*.md`.
- **Engagement-template skeletons** (`docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Think Big/Advisers/_engagement-template/**`) are exempt — they are templates, not delivered artifacts.
- **README.md files inside engagement folders** are exempt when their `audience:` is unset or J-OP — README is operator-internal navigation.

The drift gate runs at INFO until backfill closure (per RULE 6); promotes to FAIL after the render-pending tracker reaches zero entries.

## RULE 5 — Self-discipline rules for agents

When generating prose for any of the surfaces under this rule's globs, the agent must:

1. **Default to asking the audience question first.** Before authoring `.md` to a path that matches an external-delivery folder, ask: which audience tag(s) does this surface carry? If any external tag (J-IN, J-CU, J-PT, J-AD, J-ENISA, J-RC, J-CO) is in the answer, the surface needs a render trail.
2. **Co-mint the render trail with the markdown.** When authoring an external-delivery `.md`, also propose the render path in the same commit (PDF render script invocation + manifest sidecar; web link entry; ERP record id; mail render policy). The render trail is part of the deliverable, not a follow-up chore.
3. **Use the paired skill.** Read [`.cursor/skills/external-render-craft/SKILL.md`](../skills/external-render-craft/SKILL.md) before posting any external-render workflow proposal. The skill contains the per-surface render commands, the soft-success fallback policy, and the manifest schema.
4. **Refuse to send `.md` to externals.** When asked to "send X to Y" where Y is an external audience and X is a markdown file, the agent must either render X first OR surface the gap as an inline-ratify gate per [`akos-inline-ratification.mdc`](akos-inline-ratification.mdc). Never silently attach a `.md`.
5. **Track render-pending state explicitly.** If the local environment cannot render a surface (e.g., WeasyPrint not installed), the agent files an entry in [`docs/wip/planning/_trackers/external-render-pending-tracker.md`](../../docs/wip/planning/_trackers/external-render-pending-tracker.md) with the surface path + audience tags + reason + remediation owner + remediation date. The tracker is the durable governance shape for "we know this needs a render and we're not pretending it does."

## RULE 6 — Backfill posture (full backfill, ratified)

Operator ratified `full-backfill` at the rule-mint ratify gate (2026-05-19). This means:

- **Every external-facing markdown** authored before 2026-05-19 that targets a non-J-OP audience class **must reach render parity** within the bounded scope of this rule's mint commit + follow-up commits.
- **Bounded scope of "every":** the inventory is taken once at rule-mint commit; surfaces that don't yet have audience tags are inventoried + tagged + render-traced in the same pass. New surfaces created after 2026-05-19 fall under the forward-only rule (co-mint render trail).
- **Render-pending tracker** ([`docs/wip/planning/_trackers/external-render-pending-tracker.md`](../../docs/wip/planning/_trackers/external-render-pending-tracker.md)) is the durable record of any surface that the rule-mint commit + follow-ups did not reach render parity for. Each tracker row carries: surface path; audience tags; reason for pending; remediation owner; ETA. The tracker is the governance shape for "we tried; here's what's left."
- **Drift gate INFO→FAIL ramp.** While the tracker has > 0 rows, the validator runs at INFO. Once the tracker reaches zero (operator confirms in a closure decision row), the validator flips to FAIL on every release-gate run. This is the same posture pattern as `validate_brand_baseline_reality_drift.py` (INFO at I66 P2 → FAIL at I66 P7).
- **Gate flipped to FAIL on 2026-05-19** via **D-IH-86-Q** (Wave F doctrine closure). At promotion commit: render-pending tracker had zero entries, `--strict --strict-freshness` modes both PASS, all 6 external surfaces had valid manifests with current `source_sha256`. The validator now runs with `--strict --strict-freshness` in [`config/verification-profiles.json`](../../config/verification-profiles.json) (`validate_external_render_trail` step) + [`scripts/release-gate.py`](../../scripts/release-gate.py) (`run_external_render_trail_validation`). Demotion procedure (soft or hard) is documented in the paired runbook [`SOP-EXTERNAL_RENDER_GATE_PROMOTION_001`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/Tech/System%20Owner/canonicals/SOP-EXTERNAL_RENDER_GATE_PROMOTION_001.md) §6.

## RULE 7 — Channel-touchpoint cross-reference axis (advisory; codified at Wave F, 2026-05-19)

The discipline so far has named two axes: **audience** (who) + **format** (how it lands). Operator feedback at the Wave F second axis-2 ratify gate (2026-05-19) named a third axis the doctrine had not surfaced: **channel** (through which inbound / outbound channel the rendered surface reaches the recipient). This rule codifies the channel-touchpoint axis at advisory tier — it is an *enabling* layer for picking the right render-format for an audience-channel pair, not a new blocking gate.

### The 3-axis framing (audience × channel × format)

A given external surface answers three questions, not two:

1. **Audience (who?)** — answered by the `audience:` frontmatter tag, FK-resolved against [`AUDIENCE_REGISTRY.csv`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/People/Compliance/canonicals/dimensions/AUDIENCE_REGISTRY.csv) per RULE 2 (J-IN / J-CU / J-PT / J-AD / J-ENISA / J-RC / J-CO).
2. **Channel (through what inbound/outbound path?)** — optionally answered by a new `channel:` frontmatter tag, FK-resolved against [`CHANNEL_TOUCHPOINT_REGISTRY.csv`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/People/Compliance/canonicals/dimensions/CHANNEL_TOUCHPOINT_REGISTRY.csv) (CHAN-LINKEDIN-DM / CHAN-EMAIL-INBOUND / CHAN-EMAIL-OUTBOUND / CHAN-WEB-FORM / CHAN-CAL-SCHEDULE / CHAN-EVENT-MEETING / CHAN-AD-CAMPAIGN / etc.). When absent, the validator no-ops (channel is optional metadata; absence is not a finding).
3. **Format (in what surface shape?)** — answered by which render heuristic the surface satisfies per RULE 4 (PDF / Web / ERP / Mail / Slide / Broadcast).

### Channel × format compatibility (non-binding guidance)

Channel codes are inbound/outbound *paths*; render formats are the *shape* of the rendered surface. The mapping is many-to-many — same render format can serve multiple channels, same channel can carry multiple formats. The intent of recording channel metadata is to make audience-channel-format reasoning **legible** to the operator + agent, not to mechanically enforce a tight binding.

| Channel code | Typical formats | Notes |
|:---|:---|:---|
| CHAN-EMAIL-OUTBOUND / CHAN-EMAIL-INBOUND | `mail` (body) + optionally `pdf` (attachment) | Cover email body is `mail` surface; attached dossier is `pdf` surface. Two surfaces, one channel. |
| CHAN-WEB-FORM | `web` (intake page) + `mail` (auto-acknowledge) | Form-on-site is `web`; the auto-ack reply is `mail`. |
| CHAN-LINKEDIN-DM / CHAN-LINKEDIN-POST-RESPONSE | (no 6-surface mapping) | Live conversational channel; rendered surfaces are typically external follow-ups (PDF / Web / Slide) not the DM itself. |
| CHAN-CAL-SCHEDULE | `erp` (Cal.com record) + `mail` (calendar invite) | Cal.com is an ERP-class portal; the invite body is `mail`. |
| CHAN-EVENT-MEETING | (no 6-surface mapping) | Live audio/video; render trails live in pre-meeting (PDF/Slide) + post-meeting (PDF/Mail) surfaces. |
| CHAN-AD-CAMPAIGN | `web` (landing page) + `broadcast` (shared link) | Ad-driven traffic to a landing page is `web`; the ad creative itself is `broadcast`. |

This table is **non-exhaustive and non-binding**. Future operator + agent reasoning may legitimately pair channels and formats differently — record the pairing in `channel:` + render-trail, and let the audit trail accumulate. The skill section `Surface 0` (in [`external-render-craft/SKILL.md`](../skills/external-render-craft/SKILL.md)) provides a worked-example lookup procedure.

### Drift gate behaviour

[`scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py`](../../scripts/validate_external_render_trail.py) at Wave F extends with an **INFO-only** channel-resolution sub-check: when a surface declares `channel:`, the validator FK-resolves the value against `CHANNEL_TOUCHPOINT_REGISTRY.csv` and emits an INFO finding if the code is unknown. Unknown codes never block CI — they surface as advisory hints for the operator to inventory + register. Channel-absent surfaces are unaffected; this rule does not retroactively require channel tagging.

### Why advisory at Wave F

Mandating channel tagging today would create a backfill burden on every existing external-tagged surface (the ~6 rendered artifacts that satisfy Wave E + the surfaces added since). Per the Option 5 default posture in [`akos-conflict-surfacing-and-blocker-trackers.mdc`](akos-conflict-surfacing-and-blocker-trackers.mdc), the right move is to surface the axis as advisory + let the channel tag accumulate organically on newly authored surfaces, then promote to mandatory in a follow-up wave once the inventory is meaningful. A successor initiative or wave may flip channel from optional-INFO to required-FAIL when (a) operator is ready to backfill, AND (b) the channel-format pairing table proves stable across actual engagement patterns.

